content:
@User123
Are we talking about static equilibrium or stable equilibrium here? Those seem to be two different things.

@Edjy
Cases
* Validator 2 is the only case where the vertices are given in clockwise order. Please revise Test 2 to use the same order.

Thanks.

@5DN1L If I am not wrong, I believe the correct term is stable equilibrium. From google search:

"Static equilibrium refers to an object at rest with zero net force and torque, regardless of whether it returns to that position if disturbed. Stable equilibrium describes a state where, if slightly displaced, forces or torques act to restore the object to its original position. Static is a description of motion (stationary), while stable is a description of behaviour under perturbation."

Since there is the consideration of movement under force of gravity (i.e., falling over to one side), we should be trying to find points of stable equilibria.

@ethan-alexander
"Whereas" is a valid word.

@Edjy
Even if the intended test cases avoid unstable configurations, the puzzle still concerns static equilibrium only, and the terminology should reflect that. It would help to make the statement and discussion clearer and avoid mixing different terms.

Perhaps I misunderstood the difference between static and stable equilibrium. After reading the discussion above, I am ok with using the term "static equilibrium" instead of "stable equilibrium" for this puzzle. I see that @Edjy has already corrected all previous instances of "stable equilibrium" to "static equilibrium" in the problem description, so I have no further questions on that.

@Edjy, please do clarify that when >2 polygon vertices are in contact with the ground when the polygon comes to rest, the supporting segment is defined as the segment formed by the leftmost vertex and rightmost vertex. This is obvious when thinking about this puzzle in terms of the convex hull of the polygon, but might be confusing for players initially trying to figure this out. 

Please also specify that the centroid of the polygon should lie horizontally within (and inclusive of) the two vertices of the supporting segment. Thank you!
